<paragraph id="8B8736DCB9583C05FF6B56C9B9EE3ABF" blockId="2.[151,1435,1829,1974]" pageId="2" pageNumber="403">Stations: AB: 102, 149, 175, 185, 187, 197, 354, 452. AD: 208, 259, 270, 277, 299. AM: 12, 22. AR: 55, 83, 91, 101, 114, 129, 143, 144, 186, 196, 364, 417, 459, 461, 465, 571. (MNHN S2 HER 99)</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C3226557B9583C04FF6B5695BBA53CA6" lastPageId="3" lastPageNumber="404" pageId="2" pageNumber="403" type="description">
<paragraph id="8B8736DCB9583C04FF6B5695BBA53CA6" blockId="2.[151,1436,2013,2038]" lastBlockId="3.[151,1437,151,431]" lastPageId="3" lastPageNumber="404" pageId="2" pageNumber="403">
The round and soft bodies have a thick tunic often covered with epibionts. The dorsal side and the siphons are often red in life. The siphons are distant of 1/3 of the body length and their aperture shows blue and red iridescent colours and white spots (
<figureCitation id="13032A59B9593C04FEA951F4BBBF3DDD" box="[341,457,188,213]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="5.[151,250,822,844]" captionTargetBox="[150,1436,193,801]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[150,1436,193,801]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 4. Herdmania pallida. A, dissection, scale bar = 1cm; B, anus and gonoducts (stained)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1458742/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="404">Fig. 4A,B</figureCitation>
). The dorsal tubercle is large with inrolled horns. The dorsal lamina has sharp languets. The branchial sac has an average of 9 high folds on the right side and sometimes there is a 10th incomplete fold, and a fold less on the left side. The hepatic gland is divided into 3 parts: 2 lobes on each side of the cardia and a larger lobe covering the pyloric side of the stomach (
<figureCitation id="13032A59B9593C04FD615062B8813C4A" box="[669,759,298,323]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="5.[151,250,822,844]" captionTargetBox="[150,1436,193,801]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[150,1436,193,801]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 4. Herdmania pallida. A, dissection, scale bar = 1cm; B, anus and gonoducts (stained)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1458742/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="404">Fig. 4A</figureCitation>
). The gut loop is high and widely opened (
<figureCitation id="13032A59B9593C04FB285062BF583C4A" box="[1236,1326,298,323]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="5.[151,250,822,844]" captionTargetBox="[150,1436,193,801]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[150,1436,193,801]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 4. Herdmania pallida. A, dissection, scale bar = 1cm; B, anus and gonoducts (stained)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1458742/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="404">Fig. 4A</figureCitation>
). There is one tubular and straight gonad on each body side (
<figureCitation id="13032A59B9593C04FD205006B94E3C6E" box="[732,824,334,359]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="5.[151,250,822,844]" captionTargetBox="[150,1436,193,801]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[150,1436,193,801]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 4. Herdmania pallida. A, dissection, scale bar = 1cm; B, anus and gonoducts (stained)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1458742/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="404">Fig. 4A</figureCitation>
). Oviduct and sperm duct open close to each other in simple holes. The anus has a smooth edge (
<figureCitation id="13032A59B9593C04FD86503AB8A43C82" box="[634,722,370,395]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="5.[151,250,822,844]" captionTargetBox="[150,1436,193,801]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[150,1436,193,801]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 4. Herdmania pallida. A, dissection, scale bar = 1cm; B, anus and gonoducts (stained)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1458742/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="404">Fig. 4B</figureCitation>
). There is a large velum at both siphon apertures. All tissues are filled with acicular spicules.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<caption id="DF476654B9593C04FF6B5687BEB03AEC" box="[151,1222,1999,2022]" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1458738/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="404" startId="3.[151,250,1999,2021]" targetBox="[206,1372,484,1978]" targetPageId="3">
<paragraph id="8B8736DCB9593C04FF6B5687BEB03AEC" blockId="3.[151,1222,1999,2022]" box="[151,1222,1999,2022]" pageId="3" pageNumber="404">
<emphasis id="B94CEACEB9593C04FF6B5687BB643AEC" bold="true" box="[151,274,1999,2021]" pageId="3" pageNumber="404">FIGURE 2.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="4C384D5FB9593C04FEE55687B8523AEF" authorityName=": Millar &amp; Goodbody,:" authorityYear="1974" box="[281,548,1999,2022]" class="Ascidiacea" family="Pyuridae" genus="Halocynthia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Stolidobranchia" pageId="3" pageNumber="404" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="microspinosa">
